page.title: 19KELSEY HEAD'S BUTTERFLIES
page.content: Kelsey Head is a{Butterfly reserve.} When we were there we spotted seven or eight different species of butterflies and moths. First we saw a{Bernet Moth which has seven spots on each wing. Next we saw a black and white moth which we couldn't identify. We spotted a golden moth, camouflaged as a leaf, a{Large White}butterfly and a light {Peppered Moth.} We saw a beautiful pale blue butterfly which we later found out was an{Adonis Blue.} The last butterfly we found was a bright green colour, this was a{Green Hair- {streak.} This headland is a good area for butterflies because it is coastal heathland. Whilst there we also saw lots of other wildlife, including rabbits, a grasshopper, a seven- spotted ladybird and a brightly patterned caterpillar.
